and":"London, Middlesex, England","Lathom St James, Lancashire, England":"Lathom St James, Lancashire, England","Kent, England":"Kent, England"},"nl":{"14 May 1043–29 December 1104":"14 mei 1043–29 december 1104","1043–1104":"1043–1104","1056–1127":"1056–1127","1090–1165":"1090–1165","1020–1095":"1020–1095","1022–1094":"1022–1094","14 July 1077":"14 juli 1077","1090":"1090","29 December 1104":"29 december 1104","1066":"1066","1022":"1022","1165":"1165","1043":"1043","1086":"1086","1020":"1020","1096":"1096","1095":"1095","um 1090":"circa 1090","1094":"1094","12 January 1105":"12 januari 1105","20 May 1043":"20 mei 1043","1127":"1127","1104":"1104","1056":"1056","14 May 1043":"14 mei 1043","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Lathom St James, Lancashire, England":"Lathom St James, Lancashire, England","Kent, England":"Kent, England"},"en":{"14 May 1043–29 December 1104":"14 May 1043–29 December 1104","1043–1104":"1043–1104","1056–1127":"1056–1127","1090–1165":"1090–1165","1020–1095":"1020–1095","1022–1094":"1022–1094","14 July 1077":"14 July 1077","1090":"1090","29 December 1104":"29 December 1104","1066":"1066","1022":"1022","1165":"1165","1043":"1043","1086":"1086","1020":"1020","1096":"1096","1095":"1095","um 1090":"about 1090","1094":"1094","12 January 1105":"12 January 1105","20 May 1043":"20 May 1043","1127":"1127","1104":"1104","1056":"1056","14 May 1043":"14 May 1043","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Lathom St James, Lancashire, England":"Lathom St James, Lancashire, England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Woodward","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name for a forester employed to look after the trees and game in a forest, Middle English <i>woodward</i> (from Old English <i>wudu</i> ‘wood’ + <i>weard</i> ‘guardian, protector’).","History: Henry Woodward emigrated from England in 1635 and settled first in Dorchester, MA, and subsequently in Northampton, MA. He had many prominent descendants. Another Henry Woodward, born <i>c.</i> 1646 in the British West Indies, was the first English settler in SC (1664)."],"variants":[{"name":"Woodard","meanings":["from the Norman Old French personal name <i>Odard</i>, <i>Udard</i>, Middle English <i>Wodard</i>, <i>Wudard</i>. It derives from the ancient Germanic name <i>Authard</i>, <i>Othard</i>, <i>Odard</i>, composed of the elements <i>aud-</i> ‘riches' + <i>hard-</i> ‘hard, bold’.","occupational name from Middle English <i>wode</i> ‘wood’ + <i>herde</i> ‘herd’ (Old English <i>wudu</i> + <i>hierde</i>), for a person who tended animals pastured in woodland.","post-medieval pronunciation of   Woodward  ."]},{"name":"Woodworth","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Woodward   or <b>Wadworth</b>, the latter being a habitational name from Wadworth in Yorkshire, which is derived from the Old English personal name <i>Wada</i>, <i>Wadda</i> + Old English <i>worth</i> ‘enclosure’."]},{"name":"Woodman","meanings":["English:","occupational name for a woodcutter or a forester (compare   Woodward  ), from Middle English <i>wodeman</i> ‘woodman’. In some instances this may be a variant of   Wadman  .","from the Middle English personal name <i>Wudemann</i> (Old English <i>Wuduman</i>, from <i>wudu</i> ‘wood’ + <i>mann</i> ‘man’)."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":22,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705183,"age":42,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705184,"age":52,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Henry Woodward was born on 14 May 1043, in Kent, England, his father, Siward Woodward, was 24 and his mother, Helga de Chester, was 21. He married Alice Wheaten on 14 July 1077, in Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died on 29 December 1104, in London, Middlesex, England, at the age of 61, and was buried in London, Middlesex, England."},"et":{"14 May 1043–29 December 1104":"14. mai 1043–29. detsember 1104","1043–1104":"1043–1